In masked system failure data, the candidate set of possibly failed components is conventionally assumed to degrade estimation precision as its cardinality grows. We show that for exponential series systems, a deterministic masking mechanism that injectively maps each failure cause to a unique candidate set recovers the complete-identification Fisher information matrix—regardless of the candidate set cardinality. Information loss from masking is thus a property of the masking mechanism, not the masking cardinality. We verify this result numerically via Monte Carlo simulation.
